2) Data Preprocessing¶

In [12]:
# Drop the 'Id' column as it is not needed for classification.
dataset = dataset.drop('Id', axis = 1)

Determine features and labels¶

In [13]:
# Drop the 'Species' column from the dataset and store remaining columns in X (features).
X = dataset.drop('Species', axis = 1)
# Store the 'Species' column in y (target variable).
y = dataset['Species']

Lable Encoding¶

Species is a categorical variables. Therefore, we need to convert Species into numbers:

  • Iris-setosa correspond to 0
  • Iris-versicolor correspond to 1
  • Iris-virginica correspond to 2
In [14]:
# Convert categorical labels in y to numeric values.
le = LabelEncoder()
y = le.fit_transform(y)

Splitting dataset into training and test sets¶

  • Training set: Used to build the classifier
  • Test set: Used to evaluate the classifier's performance
In [15]:
# Split the data into training and testing sets.
# The training set will comprise 80%, and the test set will make up 20%.
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size = 0.2, random_state = 0)
In [16]:
#120 rows used for training (80%).

3) Build a classification model using Random Forest¶

Using RandomForestClassifier from sklearn to build the Random Forest classification model

In [20]:
# Initializing the RandomForest model with 100 trees and fixing the random state to 0 for reproducibility.
rf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=0)
In [21]:
# fit data to the model.
rf.fit(X_train, y_train)
Out[21]:
RandomForestClassifier(random_state=0)

Feature Importance¶

In [31]:
# Feature importance in order.
rf.feature_importances_
Out[31]:
array([0.10282024, 0.03010785, 0.42017676, 0.44689514])
In [32]:
# Create a Series object to identify the important features.
feature_imp = pd.Series(rf.feature_importances_,index=X_train.columns).sort_values(ascending=False)
feature_imp
Out[32]:
PetalWidthCm     0.446895
PetalLengthCm    0.420177
SepalLengthCm    0.102820
SepalWidthCm     0.030108
dtype: float64
Visualize the feature importance¶
In [33]:
# Creating a bar plot.
sns.barplot(x=feature_imp, y=feature_imp.index)
plt.xlabel('Feature Importance Score')
plt.ylabel('Features')
plt.title("Visualizing Important Features")
plt.show()

We can see that PetalWidthCm is the most important feature. Additionally, the importance of the SepalWidthCm attribute is very low, so we can exclude it and use only the remaining 3 features to build the classifier

Model Evaluation¶

Accuracy of our model is equal 100.0 %.

We can see that after removing the SepalWidthCm feature, the model's accuracy doesn't change significantly. This can be explained by the fact that SepalWidthCm is not an important feature, so it can be excluded when building the model.
